Classification of Variables

sessions_per_day = Discrete

perceived_stress_score = Discrete

country = Nominal

daily_active_minutes_instagram = Continuous

sleep_hours_per_night = Continuous

relationship_status = Nominal

income_level = Ordinal

exercise_hours_per_week = Continuous

weeky_work_hours = Continuous

Potential questions

How much does the amount of sessions on instagram in one day impact someones perceived stress?

How much time on instagram do people in the United States under the age of 25 grouped by education level have?

How many hours on Instagram does a married person in the United States have?

Plots

instagram %>%
  filter(country == "United States", age < 25, employment_status == "Student") %>%
  ggplot(aes(sessions_per_day, perceived_stress_score, color = education_level)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.2)

instagram %>%
  filter(country == "United States", age < 25) %>%
  ggplot(aes(daily_active_minutes_instagram, fill = education_level)) + geom_histogram() + facet_wrap(~education_level)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value `binwidth`.

Extra Column

instagram = mutate(instagram, active = weekly_work_hours + exercise_hours_per_week)

Average of Daily Minutes on Instagram by Education Level

instagram %>%
  filter(country == "United States", age < 25) %>%
  group_by(education_level) %>%
  summarize(avg_daily = mean(daily_active_minutes_instagram))

## 5                            565
## 6                            565

What you can see by arranging this data is the difference between the person with the lowest amount of minutes daily on instagram and the person with the highest amount of minutes daily on instagram

DPLYR Manipulation

instagram %>%
  filter(country == "United States", age < 25, employment_status == "Student") %>%
  mutate(daily_range = cut(daily_active_minutes_instagram, breaks = c(0, 145, 290, 435, 580), labels = c("0-145", "146-290", "291-435", "436-580"), right = TRUE, include.lowest = TRUE)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(daily_range)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(perceived_stress_score, fill = daily_range)) + geom_histogram() + facet_wrap(~daily_range)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value `binwidth`.

Looking at the plot, filtering the data by age and country. Using the new column daily_range which is splitting the daily_active_minutes into 6 separate bins, and comparing it with stress score. It can be seen that the lower amount of daily minutes on Instagram led to lower amounts of stress.
